---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="LEO PNT: The Slow and Steady Rise of a New Navigation Layer">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container blog-container">

      <div class="blog-header">
        <span class="badge">Blog</span>
        <h1>LEO PNT: The Slow and Steady Rise of a New Navigation Layer</h1>
        <div class="blog-meta">
          <span>April 2026</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>8 min read</span>
        </div>
        <p class="blog-lead">
          For forty years, satellite navigation has meant one thing: medium Earth orbit.
          GPS, Galileo, GLONASS and BeiDou all orbit at around 20,000 km, broadcasting
          signals that arrive at your receiver roughly 60 dB below the thermal noise floor.
          It works, but barely. And the cracks are starting to show.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="blog-body">

        <p>
          Walk through any European city today and watch what happens to your GPS signal. Urban
          canyons eat satellites. Reflections off glass buildings introduce multipath that moves
          your position by metres. And increasingly, someone somewhere is running a jammer.
          The GPS World team reported that 123,000 flights were disrupted by GNSS jamming in 2025
          alone. The Baltic region has been a near-permanent jamming zone since 2022.
          Aviation, maritime, road transport and critical infrastructure are all feeling it.
        </p>

        <p>
          The conversation about what comes next has been quiet but persistent for about a decade.
          Researchers have been writing papers. Agencies have been commissioning studies. A few
          startups have been building. And now, slowly, something is actually happening.
        </p>

        <h2>Why LEO changes the physics</h2>

        <p>
          The fundamental problem with GPS signals is not the technology. It is the distance.
          At 20,200 km, the signal has spread across an enormous area by the time it reaches
          the ground. The received power is around 25 watts at the satellite and roughly
          20 femtowatts at your antenna. That is why GNSS receivers need to integrate signal
          for milliseconds just to detect it, and why a cheap consumer jammer costing £30 can
          disrupt GPS across several kilometres.
        </p>

        <p>
          LEO satellites orbit at 400 to 1,200 km. The closer you are, the stronger the signal.
          The relationship is an inverse square law, so the improvement is dramatic. Xona Space
          Systems, the furthest along commercially, reports that Pulsar signals arrive up to 100
          times stronger than GPS at equivalent transmission power. That is not a marginal
          improvement. It changes what is possible in obstructed environments, in the presence
          of interference, and in applications where GNSS today simply cannot be trusted.
        </p>

        <p>
          There is another physics benefit that gets less attention: geometry. LEO satellites
          move fast. A GPS satellite completes one orbit in about 12 hours. A LEO satellite
          at 550 km completes an orbit in roughly 90 minutes. From any point on the ground,
          a LEO satellite passes overhead in about 10 to 15 minutes. This rapid geometry change
          is actually a positioning advantage. In precise algorithms like PPP, carrier phase
          ambiguity resolution benefits enormously from rapidly changing satellite geometry.
          Convergence times that take 20 to 40 minutes with GPS can potentially be cut to
          minutes with LEO augmentation, precisely because the geometry evolves so quickly.
        </p>

        <h2>Who is actually building this</h2>

        <p>
          As of early 2026, the FrontierSI State of Market report identifies 14 dedicated LEO
          PNT programmes globally. That is up from 9 just a year earlier. Most are either
          concept or early development. A smaller number are demonstrating hardware in orbit.
          And one, Iridium, is already delivering a commercial service.
        </p>

        <p>
          Iridium's STL (Satellite Time and Location) service has been operational for several
          years using the existing Iridium broadband constellation as an opportunistic signal
          source. The signals are not designed as precision navigation signals, but the service
          provides positioning to roughly 50 metres and timing to about 100 nanoseconds. Useful,
          particularly as a GNSS backup in denied environments. It proved the concept was viable.
        </p>

        <p>
          Xona Space Systems is the most technically ambitious of the dedicated commercial
          players. Their Pulsar system launched its first production satellite, Pulsar-0, in
          June 2025. The signal-in-space user range error for Pulsar-0 has been measured at
          around 43 millimetres, a more than tenfold improvement over GPS broadcast performance.
          Pulsar-0 has been tracked in more than six countries using twelve third-party receiver
          prototypes. Trimble announced a partnership to deliver GNSS corrections via Pulsar
          satellites in March 2025. The US Air Force awarded Xona a contract to test performance
          in GPS-denied environments. The planned constellation is approximately 300 satellites.
          It is moving from experiment to infrastructure.
        </p>

        <p>
          In Europe, ESA launched its first two LEO PNT pathfinder satellites in December 2025
          under contracts with GMV and Thales Alenia Space. The mission, approved at ESA
          ministerial in 2022, is an in-orbit demonstration rather than an operational service,
          but it will validate signals across multiple frequency bands in L and S bands and
          feed directly into the design of a future EU institutional system. The Celeste
          programme, announced by France's Wheere Corporation, adds a fifteenth project to
          the growing list. Europe is not sitting still.
        </p>

        <p>
          China has been running CentiSpace experiments with real observation data from multiple
          LEO satellites, publishing positioning results that show LEO augmentation reducing PPP
          convergence times significantly compared to GNSS alone. BeiDou's PPP-B2b service,
          discussed elsewhere on this site, already delivers free corrections via GEO satellites.
          LEO augmentation of BeiDou is a logical next step and appears to be on the roadmap.
        </p>

        <h2>The engineering challenges nobody talks about enough</h2>

        <p>
          The enthusiasm around LEO PNT is justified, but the engineering challenges are real
          and deserve honest discussion.
        </p>

        <p>
          The Doppler problem is significant. A GPS satellite moves at roughly 3.9 km/s relative
          to the ground, generating Doppler shifts of up to about 4 kHz on L1. A LEO satellite
          at 550 km moves at roughly 7.6 km/s, generating Doppler shifts of up to 40 kHz on the
          same frequency. That is a tenfold increase. Receiver tracking loops are designed around
          the GPS Doppler range. Supporting LEO signals requires wider acquisition search windows,
          higher rate tracking loops, and either new hardware or very significant firmware changes.
          This is not impossible. Xona has been explicit that many existing receivers can ingest
          Pulsar signals through firmware updates. But it is not trivial either.
        </p>

        <p>
          Orbit determination is harder at LEO. GPS satellites are in stable, well-understood
          MEO orbits. LEO satellites experience atmospheric drag, solar radiation pressure and
          gravity perturbations that are significantly more complex to model precisely. Broadcast
          ephemeris accuracy for a LEO satellite degrades faster than for GPS, which means the
          ground segment needs to upload corrections more frequently. Xona's architecture uses
          GNSS inputs, ground station observations and inter-satellite links to update clock and
          ephemeris very frequently. The infrastructure cost of doing this at scale for a global
          constellation of 300 satellites is not trivial.
        </p>

        <p>
          The constellation size requirement is also much larger. GPS achieves global coverage
          with 31 satellites. Because LEO satellites move so fast and have a smaller footprint
          on the ground, you need far more of them for continuous coverage. Most LEO PNT
          concepts require 100 to 300 satellites for global service. SpaceX's Starlink has
          demonstrated that launching this many satellites is now economically feasible.
          But Starlink is a communication constellation with revenue from day one of service.
          A dedicated PNT constellation needs a different business model.
        </p>

        <h2>Signals of opportunity: the other path</h2>

        <p>
          Not every LEO PNT approach involves dedicated navigation satellites. There is a
          growing field of research and some commercial activity around using existing LEO
          broadband constellations as opportunistic positioning signals. Starlink, OneWeb and
          similar systems already have thousands of satellites broadcasting strong microwave
          signals. Work published in the Journal of the Institute of Navigation in 2025 by
          Kozhaya, Saroufim and Kassas demonstrated positioning using Starlink signals with
          accuracy of a few metres. The FCC in the United States issued a notice of inquiry
          in 2025 examining whether LEO satellites should be required to include positioning
          beacons in their signals.
        </p>

        <p>
          Signals of opportunity will not replace dedicated PNT systems for precision
          applications. The signals are not designed for it, the geometry is suboptimal
          and there are integrity concerns that matter enormously for safety-critical use cases.
          But for resilience, for backup positioning in GNSS-degraded environments, and for
          timing at the microsecond level, they are worth taking seriously. A Starlink terminal
          that also provides sub-metre positioning as a secondary function is a compelling
          product.
        </p>

        <h2>What this means for working GNSS engineers</h2>

        <p>
          If you are designing GNSS-based systems today, LEO PNT is not yet something you need
          to support. But it is something you should understand and track, for a few reasons.
        </p>

        <p>
          The receiver architecture conversation is already happening. Chipset manufacturers are
          being approached by LEO PNT providers asking for integration support. The first
          chipsets with native Pulsar support will appear in the next few years. If you are
          specifying receivers for long-lifecycle products, particularly in defence, autonomous
          vehicles or critical infrastructure, the receiver you choose today may need to support
          LEO PNT signals in its firmware lifetime.
        </p>

        <p>
          The standards conversation is beginning. The RTK community built on RTCM, and PPP
          built on the IGS SSR format. LEO PNT will need correction formats, integrity standards
          and interoperability definitions. These processes move slowly and the engineers who
          understand the technical requirements are exactly the people who should be in the room.
        </p>

        <p>
          Perhaps most importantly, LEO PNT represents a genuine architectural shift in how we
          think about satellite navigation. Since GPS became operational in 1995, the fundamental
          model has been the same: a small number of government-operated MEO satellites providing
          a free civil signal to billions of receivers. LEO PNT introduces commercial operators,
          dedicated dedicated high-precision services, authentication as a first-class feature,
          and the possibility of signals strong enough to work indoors and in urban canyons. That
          is not an incremental improvement. It is a different design point entirely.
        </p>

        <h2>The honest assessment</h2>

        <p>
          The FrontierSI report is clear that as of the end of 2025, operational maturity across
          the LEO PNT sector remains limited. Most programmes are still in concept or
          demonstration phases. Only Iridium STL is delivering a fully commercial service today,
          and it is not a precision positioning system. Xona's Pulsar constellation will need
          hundreds of satellites for global coverage and those satellites need to be launched,
          commissioned and operated reliably over years before they represent true infrastructure.
          The engineering challenges around Doppler, orbit determination and constellation size
          are real.
        </p>

        <p>
          But the trajectory is clearly upward. Fourteen programmes in late 2025, up from nine
          a year earlier. The first production LEO PNT satellite in orbit and tracking in six
          countries. ESA pathfinders in orbit. FCC inquiries. Defence contracts. Commercial
          partnerships with Trimble, Safran and others. The pieces are assembling.
        </p>

        <p>
          The rise of LEO PNT is not a revolution happening overnight. It is an infrastructure
          build that will take the better part of this decade to mature. But for those of us
          who work in GNSS, it is worth paying close attention now, while the technical
          foundations are still being laid and the standards are still being written.
          The next generation of positioning infrastructure is being designed today.
        </p>

      </div>

      <div class="blog-footer">
        <div class="bf-tags">
